ly has as its first element the derived adjective <i>beren</i> or the compound <i>bere-ærn</i> ‘barn’. There is also a place of this name in Derbyshire, named with Old English <i>bār</i> ‘boar’ or <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, and one in Shropshire, which is from <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>lēah</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Barlowe","meanings":["English: variant of   Barlow  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Barlow was born in 1376, in Derby, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Robert De Padley IV in 1395, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died on 9 March 1463, at the age of 87."},"et":{"1376–9 March 1463":"1376–9. märts 1463","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1400–1463":"1400–1463","1376–1463":"1376–1463","1400":"1400","1376":"1376","1463":"1463","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","9 March 1463":"9. märts 1463","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England","Nether Padley, Derbyshire, England":"Nether Padley, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1376–9 March 1463":"1376–9. maaliskuuta 1463","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1400–1463":"1400–1463","1376–1463":"1376–1463","1400":"1400","1376":"1376","1463":"1463","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","9 March 1463":"9. maaliskuuta 1463","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England","Nether Padley, Derbyshire, England":"Nether Padley, Derbyshire, England"},"fr":{"1376–9 March 1463":"1376–9 mars 1463","1375–Male":"1375–Décédé","1400–1463":"1400–1463","1376–1463":"1376–1463","1400":"1400","1376":"1376","1463":"1463","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","9 March 1463":"9 mars 1463","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, Angleterre","Nether Padley, Derbyshire, England":"Nether Padley, Derbyshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Joan Barlow est née en 1376, à Derby, Derbyshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé Robert De Padley IV en 1395, à Derbyshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Elle est décédée le 9 mars 1463, à l’âge de 87 ans."},"de":{"1376–9 March 1463":"1376–9. März 1463","1375–Male":"1375–Verstorben","1400–1463":"1400–1463","1376–1463":"1376–1463","1400":"1400","1376":"1376","1463":"1463","1375":"1375","1395"